metadata.name: Offset Disorder #27
metadata.description:
This work is an experiment using generated risograph halftones and hand-drawn elements to create a highly textured pattern. 

- Viewing in Chrome is recommended.
- Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. 
- Image size is 1200x1200px.

Common Features:
- Random 3 to 10 color palette using colors from p5riso
- Individual color layer shifts from 2 to 20px
- Simplex or square color noise patters
- Glitches resulting in hand-drawn shapes
- Glitch rate of 10-50% of shapes

Less Common
- Linear color distribution (top -> bottom)
- Up to 5 large hand-drawn circles
- Very high glitch rate of 50%

Rare
- Perfect color alignment with no errors

metadata.name: Esagoni #43
metadata.description:
A piece stepping away from control and leaning into minimalism, there are several factors at play to make your Esagoni unique. Both of the two hexagon colors are a random RGB value, at various luminosities.

The root of separation chooses which color takes the lead, between 1-100, 50 being evenly distributed.

The separation between the two colors can vary from 0-100, 0 is a 1% chance.

Modifiers can be either Circular or Hexagonal.

The scale of the hexagons on the grid varies from 1-100.

There is a 10% chance of a monochrome Esagoni, 5% respectively to both "Black on White" and "White on Black."


This piece can also be changed to infinite resolutions, for any frame or screen you'd like to display it on.

In live view, press:

'w' to view in 16:9

't' to view in 8x10

's' to view in 1x1

'f' to adapt to your own screen size

Double-click to save image

Enjoy :)

metadata.name: Quad-Overlaps #37
metadata.description:
A simple study in color and shape overlap by Nate Donato. This collection features a large number of generative quadrilaterals and a unique painting algorithm of tinting select overlapping sections, combining to produce a wide range of unique outputs that toe a visually pleasing line between order and chaos. Inspired by early computer art pioneers such as Georg Nees and Vera Molnár, the piece builds on their work exposing how even simplistic algorithms can lead to exciting and unexpected results.


13 possible color schemes (some with random tint variations). Multiple draw modes.
Chances for extra jumbled shapes or other rare variants.


Keyboard controls, make sure to click the window into focus to use:

Press [1] to view at native size.
Press [2] to view at large size.
Press [0] to return to default view.

Press [s] to download and save as PNG.

metadata.name: Skyfloors #7
metadata.description:
Skyfloors are a study of perspective, occlusion, color, shape and motion. Occular meditation. A visceral demonstration of noise' ability to emulate natural systems; rolling hills, an angry sea, gentle breezes, crawling skin - all wrapped in 2d isometric projection with a flamboyant twist and a minimal nod to cel animation.

Controls:

right arrow - increase speed in direction 1
left arrow - increase speed in direction 0
P - pause / play
S - save image (increase res in devtools first if you are printing)
L - switch to black outline on brightlines featured pieces
B - switch to solid background on split background featured pieces
D - disable drop shadow

These pieces are pretty feature heavy and include a couple of ultra rare surprises.

All color palettes are procedurally generated, with each edition selecting for 1 of 4 different palette functions. 2 of these functions are open source and developed by meodai:
https://twitter.com/meodai
https://github.com/meodai

https://twitter.com/p4stoboy

metadata.name: GuilCity #154
metadata.description:
GuilCity is the beginning of an exciting journey bringing Guillaume Cornet’s densely-packed cities into the generative realm with the help of Matthew’s (@frostbitten’s) magic touch.

Matthew—with his background in coding and animation—enables a new opportunity to experience these cities like never before. Numerous elements from vehicles to characters and even architecture have been given life. Interact with the city (computer mouse only): poke and peek around (even behind) in this active search & find journey! 

Each generative city fills the composition with the type of whimsical, expressive elements and characters you’ve come to know Guil for. What kinds of wacky features have you discovered yet?

—

The tech behind this project utilizes the highly compressed WEBP image format in order to provide so many full-color options. This format is great, but unfortunately Safari on desktop/laptop must be upgraded to at least version 14 and macOS to at least version 11 Big Sur to use it.

The animation system for this project was created from scratch with additional help from the PIXI.js library for individual mesh animations.

—

To find out more about your GuilCity, copy your unique operation hash and place it at the end of the following url:
• https://my.guil.city?fxhash=
(for example: https://my.guil.city?fxhash=ooezL8cffNJGSc4TfNQp3u3WnDpkg8J3zFRczLuumceoYU5QYPs)

—


The entire process has been a learning experience for both of us, adapting and exploring the many possibilities to interact with each others’ skills and ideas.

We really enjoyed building this project together and are excited as we invite you to take a dive into your very own urban playground!

Merci à tous! Cheers!
  - Guillaume Cornet, Matthew Seremet

metadata.name: Multi-Biome #95
metadata.description:
Inspired by Jose Margulis's "Alpine Landscape"

Designed to be viewed as if you're walking past on the gallery wall, Multi-Biome is an interative play on perspective and scale. Each landscape is created from between 50 and 200 planes, slicing the landscape along a single axis.

Click and drag to rotate.

Press "s" in live view to save a png.
